HTML Tags

<!DOCTYPE html>: It declares the document type as HTML5. It helps the web browser
                understand how to render the page correctly.

<html>: It is the root element that wraps all the code on the web page.

<head>: It acts as a container for metadata (hidden information) about the document,
           such as the title and links to external design files.

<meta>: It specifies details about the page for the browser. In the images, it is used
        to set the character encoding (charset="utf-8") and to make the website
        responsive to different screen sizes (viewport).

<title>: It sets the title of the web page, which is the text that appears in the web browser's top tab.

<link>: It connects the web page to external resources. Here, it is used to link a
        Bootstrap CSS file to make the page look visually appealing.

<body>: It holds all the visible content of the web page, such as text, links, and navigation bars.

<nav>: It defines a section intended for navigation links. It is used here to create the top menu bar.

<div>: It is a generic container used to group other HTML elements together. It is
        heavily used in the code to apply layout styles (like container or collapse).

<a>: It stands for "anchor" and defines a hyperlink. It allows users to click
    and navigate to different pages or sections.

<button>: It creates a clickable button. In this code, it is used to create a
        toggle button that shows or hides the navigation menu on small mobile screens.

<span>: It is an inline container used to style a small piece of text or an icon without starting a new line.

<ul>: It stands for "unordered list" and is used to group a set of items that
        do not have a specific numerical order (usually shown with bullets).

<li>: It stands for "list item" and defines an individual item within a <ul> list.

<h1> and <h3>: These are heading tags used to create titles. <h1> is the largest and
    most important heading, while <h3> is a smaller subheading.

<p>: It defines a paragraph of standard text.

<script>: It is used to embed or reference executable scripts. The code uses it at the bottom
        to load JavaScript files required for interactive website features.

Jinja Template Syntax

Jinja is a template engine used (commonly with Python frameworks like Django or Flask) to generate dynamic HTML.

{% extends 'base.html' %}: It tells the system that the current file should inherit the structure
                            and layout of a parent file named base.html.

{% block content %} and {% endblock content %}: These tags create a designated placeholder. The parent file
                                                defines the block, and the child file fills that specific block
                                                with its own unique content.

{% for ... in ... %} and {% endfor %}: This creates a loop. The system uses it to go through a list of
                                        data one by one. For example, it repeatedly generates list items (<li>)
                                        for every meal available in a database.

{{ variable_name }}: The double curly braces are used to print the actual data onto the screen.
                    For example, {{ row.meal }} prints the name of the food item, and {{ row.price }} prints its cost.

{% url 'name' %}: It dynamically generates a web address. Instead of hardcoding a link,
                    the system looks up the correct URL associated with a specific page name (like 'home' or 'about').

Conditionals (Jinja)

Conditionals act as decision-makers in the code, showing certain content only if specific rules are met.

{% if condition %}: It checks if a statement is true. In the first image,
                    {% if row.meal_type == meal.0 %} checks if a specific food item matches
                    the current meal category being displayed. Another line, {% if row.status == 0 %},
                    likely checks if an item is currently available or out of stock.

{% else %}: It provides a backup plan. If the first {% if %} condition is false, the system executes
            the code inside the {% else %} block instead.

{% endif %}: It simply marks the end of the conditional decision block.

The href Attribute

href: It stands for "Hypertext Reference". It is an attribute placed inside an anchor tag (<a>).
        Its sole job is to specify the destination URL or web address that the user will be taken
        to when they click the link.

Usage in the code: Instead of using standard web links (like href="www.example.com"),
                  the code combines the href attribute with Jinja URL tags (e.g., href="{% url 'home' %}").
                  This ensures that the links automatically point to the correct internal pages generated by the server.
